<Layout title="Jeffery - Infographic Mini Project" bgcolor="bg-white">
    <header class="content-header listicle-header">

        <section class="bredcrumbs-section">
            <h1 class="content-hed listicle-hed"><span class="" style="">Here Are The Major Types Of Red Wine</span>
            </h1>
            <div class="content-dek listicle-dek" style="">
                <p>Never get embarrassed in a wine store again!</p>
            </div>
        </section>




    </header>
    <main>
        <section id="CabernetSauvignon">

            <div class="listicle-slide-hed">

                <h1>
                    <span class="listicle-slide-hed-number">1</span>
                    <span class="listicle-slide-hed-text">Cabernet Sauvignon</span>
                </h1>
                <br>
                <img alt="Wine pour with cheese and grapes" title="Wine pour with cheese and grapes"
                    src="https://hips.hearstapps.com/hmg-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/images/wine-pour-with-cheese-and-grapes-royalty-free-image-1568309227.jpg?crop=1xw:1xh;center,top&amp;resize=480:*">
                <p>The most planted grape in the world is cabernet sauvignon, and it's a safe (yet sophisticated!) bet
                    to order at just about any meal to please the whole group. While California Cabs can be a bit
                    fruitier, and French Cabs a bit more herbal, a glass is always interesting to drink as you look for
                    notes of cherries and currants, as well as spices. </p>
                <p><strong>Drink with: </strong>just about any meat, especially if it's fatty. A Cabernet Sauvignon
                    would be delicious with a burger, short rib, or lamb. </p>
            </div>

        </section>
        <br>

        <section id="Merlot">

            <h1>
                <span class="listicle-slide-hed-number">2</span>
                <span class="listicle-slide-hed-text">Merlot</span>
            </h1>
            <br>
            <img alt="Close-Up Of Merlot Grapes On Vine" title="Close-Up Of Merlot Grapes On Vine"
                src="https://hips.hearstapps.com/hmg-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/images/close-up-of-merlot-grapes-on-vine-royalty-free-image-1568310737.jpg?crop=1xw:1xh;center,top&amp;resize=480:*">
            <div class="listicle-slide-hed">


                <p>Merlot is the second-most planted grape, and it's a great entry point for someone trying to get into
                    red wine. The wine is really "easy" to drink, meaning it's fruity and yummy and won't make your
                    mouth pucker up with tannins.</p>
                <p><strong>Drink with: </strong>poultry, like duck or chicken.</p>
            </div>

        </section>

        <div class="clr"></div>

        <section id="PinotNoir">
            <div class="listicle-slide-hed">
                <h1>
                    <span class="listicle-slide-hed-number">3</span>
                    <span class="listicle-slide-hed-text">Pinot Noir</span>
                </h1>

                <br>
                <img alt="Red wine pouring from a decanter to a wine glass"
                    title="Red wine pouring from a decanter to a wine glass" class="lazyimage lazyloaded"
                    data-src="https://hips.hearstapps.com/hmg-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/images/red-wine-pouring-from-a-decanter-to-a-wine-glass-royalty-free-image-1568313635.jpg?crop=1xw:1xh;center,top&amp;resize=480:*"
                    src="https://hips.hearstapps.com/hmg-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/images/red-wine-pouring-from-a-decanter-to-a-wine-glass-royalty-free-image-1568313635.jpg?crop=1xw:1xh;center,top&amp;resize=480:*">

                <p>Among the lightest and most delicate wines with this hue, Pinot Noir won't punch you in the face like
                    some reds can; it has a "light body" in the lingo and feels silky to the tongue. You might taste
                    bright berries like raspberry or cranberry. </p>
                <p><strong>Drink with: </strong>sushi or salmon. Yes, you can drink red wine with fish! </p>
            </div>

        </section>

        <section id="Syrah">
            <h1>
                <span class="listicle-slide-hed-number">4</span>
                <span class="listicle-slide-hed-text">Syrah / Shiraz</span>
            </h1>
            
            <br>
            <img alt="Spanish food: Manchego cheese, spanish chorizo and red wine on rustic wooden table"
                title="Spanish food: Manchego cheese, spanish chorizo and red wine on rustic wooden table"
                class="lazyimage lazyloaded"
                data-src="https://hips.hearstapps.com/hmg-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/images/manchego-cheese-spanish-chorizo-and-red-wine-on-royalty-free-image-1568311304.jpg?crop=1xw:1xh;center,top&amp;resize=480:*"
                src="https://hips.hearstapps.com/hmg-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/images/manchego-cheese-spanish-chorizo-and-red-wine-on-royalty-free-image-1568311304.jpg?crop=1xw:1xh;center,top&amp;resize=480:*">
            <div class="listicle-slide-hed">


                <p>Called Syrah in France and other European countries, and Shiraz in Australia, South America, and
                    elsewhere, this wine is just plain fun to sip onâ€”it can be peppery, spicy, and bold, with the flavor
                    of rich fruits like blackberry. Break this one out after a long day when you want to sit with a book
                    and a glass of wine and really taste something.</p>
                <p><strong>Drink with: </strong>a charcuterie plate, because it'll play off all the salt and spice and
                    subtle flavors in the cheese and meats. </p>
            </div>

        </section>
    </main>

</Layout>




